    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "We will see that the `for` keyword can be used on many other data types, such as lists, sets.\n",
        "Basically, in the `for` structure after the `in` keyword there must be an object that can provide data (i.e., an iterator).\n",
        "The composite structures mentioned so far (tuple, list, dict) are all such, and so are generators.\n",
        "The most common generator in a `for` loop is `range()`, which generates a range of numbers."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "aifVs4z4bGQS"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "for x in range(10, 20, 5): # start at 10, stop before 20, step by 5\n",
        "    print(\"the generated number:\", x)"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "DSJhYDmc3pI5"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "The `range()` function only requires the first parameter, which in that case represents the last (exclusive) generated number; the starting element is 0 and the step is 1.\n",
        "Example:"
